snippet.textDisplay:
here we go, this video is already disappointing to me.

I have cheated on someone and it is one of the only things I regret in life. He trusted me as his best friend (we were good friends before we dated) and I broke that trust. Yes I had a lot of things going on mentally that lead me to do it but at the end of the day I made a decision that I knew would hurt him but chose to do it anyways. He didn’t deserve that.
Looking back on it and reflecting I feel like so many people wouldn’t be cheaters or cheated on if they had clear expectations and thorough communication of the relationship from the beginning but monogamy is so programmed in us that thinking of being in something not monogamous seems weird when you’re young. This happened to me in high school because I was justifying that being with girls wasn’t the same thing as being with another male. But no. I was confused and very wrong. There is no excuse for having multiple partners secretly and I will never lie to someone I am intimate with again because nobody deserves that.
I know that I am a very different person than who I was when I cheated and I can confidently say that it will not happen again. Trust is sacred.
I am posting this so people can get another perspective please do not attack me because I know the internet is insane:’)

snippet.textDisplay: (Almost) everyone in the comments is hating on either the people in this video or cheaters in general, we can all agree that cheating is bad but cheaters have their own reasons, of course they shouldn't have done it but I'm sure they either already learned from it or will learn from it and won't do it again, they feel guilty and feel bad about it, so why make them feel even worse? Besides, it's a good thing if they can come to terms with their past and move on and a lot of times that involves forgiving yourself, otherwise you won't stop feeling guilty and it will just hurt you. I've seen/heard the effect of forgiving someone's terrible actions which for most people are unforgivable, if I can believe those people, its relieving and helps you move on from the past. Why won't you allow someone to feel that way just because their forgiving themselves? Everyone makes mistakes, some make worse then others but everyone deserves forgiveness as long as they actually learn from their mistake(s) and become a better person.

snippet.textDisplay:
"Once a cheater, always a cheater"
Yes and no, it depends a lot on what sort of person you are dealing with. Some people do it hoping for an escape and those kinds of people are usually more likely to regret it. Mainly because they realize how unfair it is to their loved one and themselves. Now, people that do it out of impulse and thrill, that is much more difficult, the rise they get out of the situation can be addiction and hard to control. Even when the person stops, just like a person with your typical addiction, when faced with an opportunity, they tend to fall into the habit again.

P.S: I understand these people (some of them...) have involved pass their actions, but I doubt they truly regret what they did to the extent they claim. Why? Their answers seem to try to excuse their behavior, and even some of them probably would do it again, they are just not going to admit it on camera.

snippet.textDisplay:
What's throwing everyone off is the fantasied measure people place on relationships. This is how your freedom of thought & expression works against you. Because you're free to adhere to belief, you're equipped only with your expectations & principles. That's like assuming you're set to brave the icy woods with a "lucky" hat. Your moral argument, any moral argument, won't secure you from reality's consequences or humanity's inconsistencies.

Cheating is not the "be all, end all" clause. Because humans vary, so do our loyalty to our own principles. People change, but when they want to. People cheat- when they want to. You'll get over being deceived- when you want to. There's no manufacturing a foolproof indicator to determine the path of least resistance. Whether it's a memorable smile, good teeth, an awesome talent, or even marriage of a lengthy time period- If someone wants to cheat on you, they will. It hurts less or none at all when you perceive these things outside your bubble.

Wow it’s sad to me how many judgmental comments there are. I think it was brave of them to come on here and be open/honest about their mistakes. I don’t see them really justifying their behavior. If you think about it, every action we make has some sort of reason behind it. Even if right after we realize it was a terrible decision.

I appreciated how real Vincent was. I think it’s going to be difficult for him to be faithful moving forward, but if he keeps being honest with his partners about his struggles than I really do see things starting to change for him. The right person will see that.
